üìò CompTIA Security+ ‚Äî Practice Exam Consolidation

Day 55 Overall | Day 12 of Practice Exams

Overview

Today focused primarily on completing multiple timed practice-exam sections (30 sets of 5 questions) to reinforce core Security+ concepts, improve question interpretation, and identify weak knowledge areas. While minimal new handwritten notes were produced, this session emphasized active recall, pattern recognition, and exam readiness.

üîê Core Concepts Reinforced
Authentication, Authorization & Access Control

Least Privilege: Users and systems should only have the minimum access required.

Privileged Access Management (PAM): Controls and audits administrative credentials using check-in/check-out, credential rotation, and session monitoring.

Privilege Creep: Gradual accumulation of excess permissions, often during role changes.

Federation & SSO: Authenticate once and access multiple services via trusted identity providers.

PEAP / EAP / RADIUS: Secure network authentication mechanisms commonly used in enterprise wireless environments.

üåê Network & Application Attacks

Credential Stuffing: Reusing leaked username/password pairs across services.

Password Spraying: Trying common passwords across many accounts.

CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery): Tricks authenticated users into executing unwanted actions.

Directory Traversal: Exploiting path manipulation (../) to access restricted files.

DNS Poisoning / Spoofing: Redirecting traffic by corrupting DNS records.

Evil Twin Attacks: Rogue access points impersonating legitimate Wi-Fi networks.

üõ°Ô∏è Defensive Security Controls

WAF (Web Application Firewall): Protects against XSS, SQL injection, and other web-based attacks.

NGFW: Application-aware firewall with deep packet inspection.

DLP (Data Loss Prevention): Prevents unauthorized data exfiltration.

EDR: Detects, alerts, and responds to endpoint threats in real time.

FDE (Full Disk Encryption): Protects data at rest if devices are lost or stolen.

Secure Configuration Guides: Reduce attack surface via hardened baselines.

‚òÅÔ∏è Cloud & Infrastructure Concepts

CASB: Enforces security policies between users and cloud providers.

Containers vs VMs: Lightweight, isolated application environments.

IaaS: Cloud-provided compute, storage, and networking.

Availability Zones: Physically separate data centers for high availability.

VDI: Centralized desktops accessed remotely.

üìú Risk, Governance & Continuity

BIA (Business Impact Analysis): Determines acceptable data loss and downtime.

BCP / DRP: Plans for operational continuity during disruptions.

MTTR: Mean time to repair failed systems.

SOC 2 Reports: Vendor security assurance for cloud services.

NIST 800-53: Security and privacy controls for federal systems.

ISO 27001: International ISMS standard.

üîé Vulnerability Management

CVSS: Standardized vulnerability scoring (0‚Äì10).

Credentialed vs Non-Credentialed Scans

Continuous Validation: Ongoing testing of security posture.

Nmap: Network discovery and service enumeration tool.

üß† Security Operations & Testing

Red Team: Simulated attacks (often covert).

Blue Team: Defensive monitoring and response.

Purple Team: Collaborative offense + defense.

Tabletop Exercises: Scenario-based incident response simulations.

üéØ Key Takeaways

Practice exams are increasingly reinforcing scenario recognition over rote memorization.

Many attacks differ subtly ‚Äî understanding intent, scope, and impact is critical.

Repetition is improving speed and confidence in identifying the best answer, not just a correct one.

Focus is shifting from learning new terms to exam strategy and concept linkage.
